\n**WHAT'S GOING ON**\nWPP, a massive advertising conglomerate, is tearing down the walls between its major agencies like Ogilvy, VML, and AKQA to smash them into one single operation [1]. For years, they just operated as a bunch of separate brand names sharing a corporate bank account [3]. Now, they are merging because artificial intelligence can do the creative and media tasks that used to require massive personnel structures [1]. \n\n**WHY THIS IS A BIG DEAL**\nHistorically, ad agencies made their money by throwing human hours at a problem. You need an ad campaign? They bill you for the time it takes an army of designers, copywriters, and media planners to create and distribute it [4]. But when an AI can generate visual assets and optimize ad placements in seconds, you suddenly don't need thousands of people sitting at desks doing the grunt work [1, 4]. WPP's restructuring is a glaring admission that the heavy human infrastructure the advertising world was built on is now obsolete [1]. Anyone sitting at a computer for a living should care, because this proves that when automation gets good enough, legacy corporate structures simply collapse.\n\n**UNCOMFORTABLE TRUTH**\nThe thing nobody wants to say out loud is that the advertising industry doesn't actually know how it's going to make money anymore [4]. If you can no longer bill clients for human hours, what exactly are you putting on the invoice? Agencies talk about charging for \"value\" or \"outcomes,\" but they haven't figured out how to price that, and clients are highly skeptical [4, 5]. The real friction is that clients might just take these AI tools, move their marketing in-house, and bypass the agencies completely [2, 4]. We don't yet know if this reorganization will actually save WPP, as their stock price hasn't even bumped up on the news [6].\n\n**SO WHAT**\nAgencies can no longer survive by selling human time, so they have to figure out how to sell human judgment before their clients realize they can just use the AI themselves [2, 5].",
