\n**WHAT'S GOING ON**\nPeople are letting computer programs\u2014AI agents\u2014buy their everyday stuff for them [1]. Instead of you going to the store or clicking through a website, an algorithm just picks out and orders your routine goods [1]. Because of this, companies are realizing that if you don't specifically tell the AI that you must have their specific brand, the machine will just buy whatever is easiest or cheapest [1, 3]. If a brand isn't absolutely indispensable to a human being, it is going to be quietly swapped out by the algorithm [2, 3].\n\n**WHY THIS IS A BIG DEAL**\nThe metric that actually matters to these massive companies now is something called the \"Role of Brand Index\" [3]. That is just a fancy way of measuring whether a human being actually demanded your product by name, or if a robot just brokered the deal in the background [3]. If you have a high score, people love you and actively seek you out [3]. If your score is low, the AI replaces you with a generic substitute and the consumer doesn't even care [3]. Anyone who sells anything needs to pay attention, because the middle ground is completely disappearing [2]. In the age of AI, you are either a brand people can't live without, or you are completely disposable [2].\n\n**UNCOMFORTABLE TRUTH**\nThe uncomfortable truth is that for most of the things we buy, we don't actually care about the brand. Companies spend billions trying to convince us that their ordinary products are special, but the second we hand the shopping list over to an AI, that illusion shatters [1, 3]. The machines do not care about clever commercials or brand legacy [1]. If a brand only survived because it was conveniently placed at eye-level on a supermarket shelf, it is going to be commoditized and destroyed by algorithmic curation [1, 2]. \n\n**SO WHAT**\nTo survive tomorrow, companies must build such deep, genuine human loyalty that we specifically order our AI assistants never to buy anything else [3, 4].",
