\n**WHAT'S GOING ON**\nDesign Bridge and Partners took the old, boring \"brand guideline\" PDF and turned it into a piece of working software [3, 5]. Instead of handing a client a static book that says \"use this color and this font,\" they write algorithms\u2014mathematical rules\u2014that define the brand's visual identity [3]. They then give the client a custom dashboard. With a few clicks, the client's own team can spit out variations of logos and images that automatically obey all the design rules [1, 2]. For instance, the delivery company Evri used it to create nearly 200,000 unique font combinations for their logo [4]. \n\n**WHY THIS IS A BIG DEAL**\nThink about how ad agencies normally work. A client needs a new banner ad, so they call the agency, the agency bills them for a designer's time, and days later, the ad arrives. What this technology actually means is that the bottleneck is completely gone [2]. The agency's role shifts from doing the repetitive grunt work to building the machine that *does* the grunt work [3, 6]. If you are a giant global brand like Vodafone, this means your marketing team can generate exactly what they need, exactly when they need it, in record time [1, 4]. It transfers the day-to-day creative power from the agency directly back to the client [2].\n\n**UNCOMFORTABLE TRUTH**\nHere\u2019s the part that makes traditional ad agencies sweat: this software kills the old billable-hours business model. Ad agencies traditionally make a lot of money charging for routine design tweaks. By giving the client a tool to do this themselves instantly, the agency is cutting off its own steady stream of easy revenue [1, 2]. The uncomfortable reality is that designers are programming themselves out of the repetitive parts of their jobs [3, 6]. Will clients still pay top dollar for the \"machine\" if they aren't paying for the hours? That part is still uncertain, but agencies must become high-level consultants to survive this shift [6].\n\n**SO WHAT**\nMarketing teams are no longer chained to their ad agencies for basic design work, trading static rulebooks for software that generates perfect, on-brand assets instantly [1, 2].",
