\n**WHAT'S GOING ON**\nImagine you want to find out if people will buy a new makeup product. Normally, you have to find the right people, bring them into a room, ask them questions, and decode what they actually mean. That takes a huge amount of time. NTT DATA and the cosmetics giant Kao just decided to skip all that [1, 2]. They took all the old survey answers, buying habits, and social media posts they already had and fed them into an artificial intelligence [2]. They basically created fake digital people\u2014\"AI Consumers\"\u2014and a digital interviewer to ask them questions [2]. Instead of waiting a month and a half to get answers from real humans, they got their research done in just half a day [3].\n\n**WHY THIS IS A BIG DEAL**\nThink about how fast the world moves today. People change what they like every week, not every season [3]. If it takes you six weeks just to figure out what makeup someone wants, by the time you actually manufacture it, they want something else entirely. Shrinking a six-week research cycle down to twelve hours is a 99 percent drop in time [3]. That is not just a tiny incremental improvement; it is a fundamental shift in how the physical world is built. Anyone making things for people\u2014whether it is clothes, food, or gadgets\u2014can now test hundreds of ideas a week instead of two or three. The wildest part is that NTT DATA claims the quality of the answers from these digital ghosts is equal to, or even better than, the output you get from asking real, living people [3].\n\n**UNCOMFORTABLE TRUTH**\nHere is the thing nobody wants to say out loud: we are talking about replacing human opinions with algorithms. The AI is just predicting what a person *might* say based on data about what people *used* to say [2]. Are these digital personas actually experiencing the physical product? Of course not, they do not have faces or skin! They are just recognizing patterns in historical data. But if a math equation can mimic our personal tastes so perfectly that a massive corporation no longer needs to talk to us to know what we want, it shows we might be a lot more predictable than we like to admit. There is also a real uncertainty here: if companies stop talking to real humans, we do not know if these bots will eventually just create an echo chamber of fake preferences that completely misses sudden, irrational human shifts.\n\n**SO WHAT**\nThe physical bottleneck of asking real humans for their opinions has been eliminated, meaning new products will soon be designed and tested at the blazing speed of software [2, 3].",
